1
00:03:21,330 --> 00:03:24,920
An article, which I believe appeared
in a newspaper, asked why,

2
00:03:25,130 --> 00:03:29,430
since it would seem that you are
in effect the Mayor of Chicago,

3
00:03:29,630 --> 00:03:34,140
you're not simply being
appointed to that position.

4
00:03:37,180 --> 00:03:41,690
Well, I tell ya, it's touching.
Like a lot of things in life,

5
00:03:41,900 --> 00:03:46,230
we laugh because it's funny,
and we laugh because it's true.

6
00:03:46,440 --> 00:03:48,400
Some people say,
reformers here say:

7
00:03:48,610 --> 00:03:52,570
"Put that man in jail,
what does he think he is doing?"

8
00:03:52,780 --> 00:03:56,240
What I hope I'm doing, and here's
where your paper's got a point,

9
00:03:56,450 --> 00:03:58,750
is I'm responding to
the will of the people.

10
00:04:01,710 --> 00:04:06,300
People are gonna drink. We all
know that. All I do is act on that.

11
00:04:06,510 --> 00:04:09,300
And all this talk of bootlegging.
What is bootlegging?

12
00:04:09,510 --> 00:04:13,300
On the boat it's bootlegging,
on Lake Shore Drive it's hospitality.

13
00:04:13,510 --> 00:04:15,760
I'm a businessman.

14
00:04:17,310 --> 00:04:20,980
Your reputation is that you control
your business through violence.

15
00:04:21,190 --> 00:04:25,820
That those that don't purchase your
product are dealt with violently.

16
00:04:31,280 --> 00:04:33,320
It's all right.

17
00:04:34,780 --> 00:04:36,700
I grew up in a tough neighbourhood.

18
00:04:36,910 --> 00:04:39,750
We used to say, "Y ou can get further
with a kind word and a gun"

19
00:04:39,960 --> 00:04:43,040
"than you can
with just a kind word."

20
00:04:44,380 --> 00:04:46,630
And in that neighbourhood
it might've been true.

21
00:04:46,840 --> 00:04:50,420
And sometimes
your reputation follows you.

22
00:04:51,800 --> 00:04:54,590
There is violence in Chicago,
but not by me

23
00:04:54,800 --> 00:04:59,100
and not by anybody I employ.
Because it's not good business.

24
00:05:30,090 --> 00:05:34,590
<i>Leave us alone down here,</i>
<i>we've got everything we need.</i>

25
00:05:34,800 --> 00:05:37,800
The green beer you're peddlin'
ain't any good.

26
00:05:38,010 --> 00:05:42,230
It's not supposed to be good.
It's supposed to be bought.

27
00:05:43,390 --> 00:05:46,150
I'm not buyin' any.

28
00:05:48,230 --> 00:05:52,190
Don't worry about it, Pops,
we won't come back.

29
00:05:55,280 --> 00:05:58,240
- How's everyone at your house today?
- They're fine.

30
00:05:58,450 --> 00:06:02,500
- Is your Mama well?
- She has a little cold.

31
00:06:02,700 --> 00:06:04,920
Oh, she does?

32
00:06:06,080 --> 00:06:09,290
- I'm sorry to hear that.
- But she'll be all right.

33
00:06:15,130 --> 00:06:16,890
- There you go.
- Thank you.

34
00:06:17,090 --> 00:06:22,390
That's all right, sweetie.
You be careful crossin' the street.

35
00:06:22,600 --> 00:06:25,020
- Mister!
- You tell your Mama that...

36
00:06:25,230 --> 00:06:27,770
Hey, Mister! Wait!

37
00:06:27,980 --> 00:06:31,360
Mister! Wait!
You forgot your brief...

38
00:07:36,670 --> 00:07:41,090
Yes, I heard it on the radio.

39
00:07:41,300 --> 00:07:43,680
I know.

40
00:07:43,890 --> 00:07:47,140
Now it's time to go to work.

41
00:07:55,150 --> 00:07:58,450
You'll make a good first impression.

42
00:08:06,500 --> 00:08:09,290
I love you, Eliot.

43
00:08:14,670 --> 00:08:16,000
Now, shoo.

44
00:08:17,800 --> 00:08:23,430
Eliot Ness, Special Agent
of the Treasury Department.

45
00:08:23,640 --> 00:08:26,140
- Mr Ness.
- Thank you, Chief.

46
00:08:26,350 --> 00:08:29,680
At the request
of the City of Chicago,

47
00:08:29,890 --> 00:08:33,650
the Department of the Treasury
has inaugurated a programme

48
00:08:33,860 --> 00:08:37,400
to deal with the flow of illegal
liquor and the violence it creates.

49
00:08:37,610 --> 00:08:41,400
Mr Ness!
Of what does this programme consist?

50
00:08:41,610 --> 00:08:44,450
I and other agents of the Treasury
will be working

51
00:08:44,660 --> 00:08:46,700
with the Chicago Police...

52
00:08:46,910 --> 00:08:49,120
Isn't it just another
showpiece programme?

53
00:08:49,330 --> 00:08:53,500
- What do you think of prohibition?
- Do you drink, Mr Ness?

54
00:08:53,710 --> 00:08:57,590
- Come on, answer the questions.
- It's not just a showpiece.

55
00:08:57,800 --> 00:09:01,010
And I'll tell you
how I feel about prohibition.

56
00:09:01,220 --> 00:09:02,630
It is the law of the land.

57
00:09:02,840 --> 00:09:05,600
Do you consider yourself
a crusader, is that it?

58
00:09:05,800 --> 00:09:08,140
What qualifications
do you have for the job?

59
00:09:08,350 --> 00:09:10,730
Do you have any political ambitions?

60
00:09:10,930 --> 00:09:13,650
All right, boys,
I think that's enough.

61
00:09:16,060 --> 00:09:19,280
What are your real plans?
What have you got coming up?

62
00:09:19,480 --> 00:09:21,570
You'll have to read about it
in the paper.

63
00:09:21,780 --> 00:09:25,450
- Let me ride along with you.
- No. Can't help you.

64
00:09:25,660 --> 00:09:28,910
Mr Ness, Lieutenant Alderson,
the Flying Squad.

65
00:09:29,120 --> 00:09:32,080
Are you ready to meet the men?

66
00:09:33,460 --> 00:09:35,500
Yes, I am.

67
00:09:45,300 --> 00:09:48,310
I have one more thing to say.

68
00:09:52,100 --> 00:09:55,440
I know that many of you take a drink.

69
00:09:55,650 --> 00:09:59,520
What you've done before today
is not my concern.

70
00:09:59,730 --> 00:10:03,280
But now we must be pure,
and I want you to stop.

71
00:10:04,650 --> 00:10:09,080
It's not a question of whether it's
'a harmless drink'. It may well be.

72
00:10:09,280 --> 00:10:10,870
But it's against the law.

73
00:10:11,080 --> 00:10:15,330
And as we are going to enforce
the law, we must do first by example.

74
00:10:20,130 --> 00:10:22,710
Are there any questions?

75
00:10:24,090 --> 00:10:27,470
Good. The Department
of the Treasury's had

76
00:10:27,680 --> 00:10:29,810
a man undercover here
for some time now.

77
00:10:30,010 --> 00:10:32,060
We've received word
from this informant

78
00:10:32,270 --> 00:10:35,770
that a large shipment of Canadian
whiskey has arrived in Chicago.

79
00:10:35,980 --> 00:10:38,690
So I hope that you have signed on
for some action.

80
00:10:46,740 --> 00:10:51,370
Remember, the liquor cases
are marked with the red maple leaf.

81
00:10:51,580 --> 00:10:54,830
The Treasury Agent is
in a grey suit with a white scarf.

82
00:10:55,040 --> 00:10:59,630
- He is not to be arrested.
- A grey suit and a white scarf.

83
00:10:59,840 --> 00:11:04,210
- That's it. Are your men ready?
- Yes, sir. They are.

84
00:11:11,140 --> 00:11:14,640
- At ease.
- Smoke 'em if you got 'em.

85
00:11:20,900 --> 00:11:23,480
- How are we doin'
- Okay.

86
00:11:29,360 --> 00:11:32,950
- Want part of a sandwich?
- No, thank you, sir.

87
00:11:39,420 --> 00:11:42,130
- You nervous?
- No, sir.

88
00:11:44,130 --> 00:11:47,920
- Been with the unit long?
- A short while.

89
00:11:49,300 --> 00:11:53,010
- I suppose we all want to do well.
- Yes, sir.

90
00:11:58,890 --> 00:12:01,730
A message from my wife.

91
00:12:02,810 --> 00:12:06,230
- You married?
- Yes, sir, I am.

92
00:12:06,440 --> 00:12:09,240
Nice to be married, huh?

93
00:12:26,340 --> 00:12:28,220
Just follow me.

94
00:13:10,260 --> 00:13:13,050
- Oh, God...
- Federal officer. Hands in the air.

95
00:13:13,260 --> 00:13:15,600
Get 'em up. Drop it.

96
00:13:15,800 --> 00:13:18,390
Damn it, I can't , it'll break.

97
00:13:19,470 --> 00:13:21,980
Mr Ness. Look, I was just...

98
00:13:22,190 --> 00:13:24,230
Geez, I'm sorry.

99
00:13:26,230 --> 00:13:29,990
Listen, I can do a lot for you,
what you're tryin' to do.

100
00:13:30,190 --> 00:13:32,400
I get the big scoop,
you make a big splash.

101
00:13:32,610 --> 00:13:37,120
Get some support. What do you say?
Let's be real, let me help you.

102
00:13:37,330 --> 00:13:39,540
Okay. Just shut up.

103
00:14:06,100 --> 00:14:08,940
All right now...
Let's do some good!

104
00:14:22,830 --> 00:14:24,330
Hold it right there!

105
00:14:26,920 --> 00:14:31,590
Federal officer. You're under arrest
for violations of the Volstead Act.

106
00:14:40,470 --> 00:14:43,520
Let's cover the doors!
Don't let anybody out!

107
00:14:45,310 --> 00:14:47,520
Preseuski.

108
00:14:48,610 --> 00:14:51,730
- I'm here with permission.
- Who gave you permission?

109
00:14:51,940 --> 00:14:54,860
- Mr Ness!
- Sorry, let him through here.

110
00:14:55,860 --> 00:14:58,620
Let him through here.

111
00:14:59,740 --> 00:15:02,950
You want to take your picture,
take it now.

112
00:15:04,040 --> 00:15:06,460
- You ready?
- Ready.

113
00:15:32,570 --> 00:15:34,610
Liquor, huh?

114
00:15:37,070 --> 00:15:39,070
Get him out of here.

115
00:15:39,280 --> 00:15:43,370
- Tear the place apart!
- I mean now, get him out!

116
00:15:47,960 --> 00:15:50,540
That means you, too.

117
00:15:55,380 --> 00:15:57,260
Christ!

118
00:17:15,590 --> 00:17:19,300
Now, what do you think you're doing?

119
00:17:19,510 --> 00:17:24,390
You want to throw garbage? Throw it
in the goddamn trash basket.

120
00:17:24,590 --> 00:17:27,810
Don't you have
more important things to do?

121
00:17:28,060 --> 00:17:30,180
Yeah.

122
00:17:30,390 --> 00:17:32,980
But I'm not doing them right now.

123
00:17:34,060 --> 00:17:36,860
Do we understand each other?

124
00:17:40,240 --> 00:17:42,990
Okay, pal, why the Mohaska?

125
00:17:44,410 --> 00:17:48,240
- Why are you packin' the gun?
- I'm a Treasury Officer.

126
00:17:51,200 --> 00:17:53,370
All right.

127
00:17:53,580 --> 00:17:57,290
Just remember
what we talked about now.

128
00:18:01,260 --> 00:18:03,680
Hey... Wait a minute!

129
00:18:03,880 --> 00:18:07,640
What the hell kind of police
do you have in this goddamn citÃ½?

130
00:18:07,850 --> 00:18:10,720
You just turned your back
on an armed man.

131
00:18:10,930 --> 00:18:14,690
- You're a Treasury officer.
- I just told you I was.

132
00:18:14,900 --> 00:18:18,020
Who would claim to be that,
who was not?

133
00:18:23,900 --> 00:18:26,990
What's your name and unit?

134
00:18:30,700 --> 00:18:33,330
It's right here.

135
00:18:34,750 --> 00:18:38,130
You got a beef?
What is it?

136
00:18:40,550 --> 00:18:43,590
How did you know I had a gun?

137
00:18:43,800 --> 00:18:47,590
What do you want,
a free lesson in police work?

138
00:18:49,970 --> 00:18:51,310
No.

139
00:18:54,730 --> 00:18:56,600
Are you okay, pal?

140
00:18:58,400 --> 00:19:01,150
I had a rough day on the job.

141
00:19:02,780 --> 00:19:05,860
- Are you going home now?
- I was about to.

142
00:19:08,820 --> 00:19:12,830
Well, then, you just fulfilled
the first rule of law enforcement.

143
00:19:16,920 --> 00:19:20,880
Make sure when your shift is over
you go home alive.

144
00:19:21,960 --> 00:19:24,210
Here endeth the lesson.

145
00:20:22,360 --> 00:20:27,190
$100,000 for 40 barrels.
Make sure there are no empties.

146
00:20:27,400 --> 00:20:30,490
I'm gonna give you the ledger,
everything is in the book.

147
00:20:30,700 --> 00:20:33,660
55 gallons to the barrel.

148
00:20:47,550 --> 00:20:50,260
- It's Eddie.
- <i>Come in, Eddie.</i>

149
00:21:14,370 --> 00:21:20,040
So, he gets into the snowplough,
and he says, "Let's do some good" .

150
00:21:20,250 --> 00:21:22,670
And then, we bust through...

151
00:22:11,630 --> 00:22:15,260
- Mr Ness?
- Yes?

152
00:22:15,470 --> 00:22:18,810
I came here to thank you.

153
00:22:19,010 --> 00:22:20,430
It was...

154
00:22:20,640 --> 00:22:24,440
..my little girl that got killed
with that bomb.

155
00:22:25,940 --> 00:22:27,770
I'm sorry. Please.

156
00:22:29,440 --> 00:22:31,940
I'm ...l'm so sorry.

157
00:22:33,030 --> 00:22:37,950
You see, it's ...because I know
that you have children, too.

158
00:22:39,030 --> 00:22:44,290
And that this is real for you,
that these men cause us tragedy.

159
00:22:44,500 --> 00:22:48,210
And I know that you will
put a stop to them.

160
00:22:49,290 --> 00:22:51,090
And you do that, now.

161
00:23:48,100 --> 00:23:51,400
- What do you want?
- I'd like to talk to you.

162
00:23:53,650 --> 00:23:55,780
Come in.

163
00:23:59,200 --> 00:24:02,160
I need a small group of men,
handpicked, starting with you.

164
00:24:02,370 --> 00:24:06,330
Ness! I am just a poor beat cop.

165
00:24:07,330 --> 00:24:12,750
- Now, how can <i>I help you?</i>
- Just work with me.

166
00:24:12,960 --> 00:24:16,550
- But why should I, though?
- Because you're a good cop.

167
00:24:18,010 --> 00:24:20,640
- How do you know that?
- You told me.

168
00:24:21,430 --> 00:24:23,850
If I'm such a good cop...

169
00:24:25,140 --> 00:24:28,140
How come I'm walkin' the beat,
then, at my age?

170
00:24:28,350 --> 00:24:30,270
Do you want to tell me?

171
00:24:30,480 --> 00:24:33,360
Well, maybe I'm that
Whore with a Heart of Gold.

172
00:24:33,570 --> 00:24:37,320
Or The One Good Cop in the Bad Town?
Is that what you want to hear?

173
00:24:37,530 --> 00:24:39,530
I didn't ask you, and I don't care!

174
00:24:39,740 --> 00:24:43,490
You want to stay on the beat?
You do that.

175
00:24:43,700 --> 00:24:48,040
If you'd like to come with me,
I need your help.

176
00:24:50,000 --> 00:24:51,710
I'm askin' you for help.

177
00:24:55,800 --> 00:24:59,670
Well...that's the thing you fear,
isn't it?

178
00:25:03,390 --> 00:25:08,680
Mr Ness, I wish I'd met you
ten years and...twenty pounds ago.

179
00:25:08,890 --> 00:25:14,610
But...I just think it got...
more important to me...

180
00:25:14,820 --> 00:25:16,530
..to stay alive.

181
00:25:23,820 --> 00:25:27,830
And that's why I'm walkin' the beat.
Thank you, no.

182
00:25:42,180 --> 00:25:45,800
<i>That's good, Andy. Let's start up</i>
<i>the thing and take a little ride.</i>

183
00:25:46,010 --> 00:25:48,560
<i>I wanna hear</i>
<i>that Stutz Bearcat engine, boy!</i>

184
00:25:48,770 --> 00:25:52,100
- <i>Yeah, let me open the door here.</i>
- <i>Yeah, go ahead.</i>

185
00:25:52,310 --> 00:25:55,730
<i>Whoopsy daisy,</i>
<i>pick up the door there, Andy.</i>

186
00:25:55,940 --> 00:25:59,860
<i>Throw it in the back seat.</i>
<i>Now, let me get the thing started.</i>

187
00:26:00,070 --> 00:26:02,110
<i>Yeah, start it up, Andy.</i>

188
00:26:09,080 --> 00:26:12,160
<i>Holy mackerel, Andy!</i>
<i>Listen to that Bearcat motor!</i>

189
00:26:12,370 --> 00:26:17,090
<i>Yeah, it sounds like the bear</i>
<i>is chasin' that cat all round it!</i>

190
00:26:18,800 --> 00:26:20,800
<i>Andy! She's boilin' over!</i>

191
00:26:31,850 --> 00:26:34,770
- Mr Ness?
- Yes.

192
00:26:34,980 --> 00:26:37,400
Oscar Wallace.

193
00:26:39,230 --> 00:26:42,320
I've been assigned here
by the Washington Bureau.

194
00:26:42,530 --> 00:26:44,780
- Really?
- Yes.

195
00:26:44,990 --> 00:26:49,700
Well, I'm glad to have you here,
Mr Wallace. Would you excuse me?

196
00:26:50,790 --> 00:26:53,620
We are a little in the dark here,
but any ideas you may have...

197
00:26:53,830 --> 00:26:55,790
Well, actually, yes, sir, I do.

198
00:26:56,000 --> 00:26:59,880
And the one I want to try first...
is this.

199
00:27:03,470 --> 00:27:07,550
He has not filed a return since 1926.

200
00:27:09,100 --> 00:27:12,770
- A return...?
- An income tax return.

201
00:27:14,270 --> 00:27:15,770
- Income tax.
- Yes, sir.

202
00:27:15,980 --> 00:27:20,400
- What do you do at the Bureau?
- Oh, I'm an accountant.

203
00:27:21,480 --> 00:27:25,610
- An accountant?
- Yes, and the Bureau sent me here...

204
00:27:26,700 --> 00:27:28,910
Would you excuse me?

205
00:27:32,240 --> 00:27:34,660
Please.

206
00:28:00,230 --> 00:28:02,690
Okay. Let's go.

207
00:28:02,900 --> 00:28:06,820
- Where are we going?
- These walls have ears.

208
00:28:09,570 --> 00:28:13,740
You said you wanted to know
how to get Capone.

209
00:28:16,080 --> 00:28:20,460
Do you really want to get him?
You see what I'm saying?

210
00:28:20,670 --> 00:28:25,260
- What are you prepared to do?
- Everything within the law.

211
00:28:25,460 --> 00:28:28,430
And then what are you
prepared to do?

212
00:28:28,630 --> 00:28:31,010
If you open the ball
on these people,

213
00:28:31,220 --> 00:28:33,760
you must be prepared
to go all the way.

214
00:28:33,970 --> 00:28:37,140
Because they won't give up the fight
until one of you is dead.

215
00:28:37,350 --> 00:28:39,440
I want to get Capone.
I don't know how.

216
00:28:39,640 --> 00:28:44,520
Here's how you get Capone:
he pulls a knife, you pull a gun.

217
00:28:44,730 --> 00:28:47,490
He sends one of yours to hospital,
you send one of his to the morgue!

218
00:28:47,690 --> 00:28:51,320
That's the Chicago way!
And that's how you get Capone.

219
00:28:53,620 --> 00:28:56,830
Now, do you want to do that?

220
00:28:57,040 --> 00:28:59,750
Are you ready to do that?

221
00:29:01,370 --> 00:29:05,380
I'm making you a deal.
Do you want this deal?

222
00:29:06,420 --> 00:29:08,840
I have sworn to put this man away,

223
00:29:09,050 --> 00:29:14,220
with any and all legal means
at my disposal, and I will do so.

224
00:29:22,060 --> 00:29:25,400
Well, the Lord hates a coward.

225
00:29:32,570 --> 00:29:35,780
Do you know what a blood oath is,
Mr Ness?

226
00:29:35,990 --> 00:29:38,950
- Yes.
- Good. 'Cause you just took one.

227
00:29:41,000 --> 00:29:44,210
How do you think Capone knew
about your raid the other night?

228
00:29:44,420 --> 00:29:48,050
- Somebody on the cops told him.
- Right. Welcome to Chicago.

229
00:29:48,260 --> 00:29:51,720
This town stinks
like a whorehouse at low tide.

230
00:29:51,930 --> 00:29:56,430
First, who can you trust?
Nobody. The cops, nobody.

231
00:29:56,640 --> 00:30:01,390
- 'Cause nobody wants you here.
- Then why are you helping me?

232
00:30:01,600 --> 00:30:04,600
Because I swore to uphold the law.

233
00:30:04,810 --> 00:30:07,650
And if you believe that,
I'll tell you another.

234
00:30:07,860 --> 00:30:12,110
